Fix race condition in sendSnapshotToPage_.

Fix race condition in connectToParentWindow.

Previously there was time for a snapshot to come in after the "hello"
was sent but before the onmessage listener was attached. By moving the
channel create into the setImmediate callback we can avoid this, and
also unify code between the cases.
Add missing require.

Fix race condition in sendSnapshotToPage_.

There are two asyncronous events that occur when a snapshot is
requested: the child window is opened, and the buffers are collected.
They can complete in either order, but currently if the page manages to
open and do the postMessage before the data is available, then we never
find out about the child.

This is fixed by introducing a Result for the child channel.

Merge pull request #488 from IgorMinar/patch-1

fix(wtf-call-tracing): prevent Chrome from making /null requests

fix(wtf-call-tracing): prevent Chrome from making /null requests

The latest version (2014.1.23.1) of the Chrome extension breaks on all apps I've tried because during instrumentation all script tags are transformed into script tags that load scripts from `{base}/null` url.

So given:

```html
<script src="myScript.js"></script>
```

I end up with

```
<script src="null">
  // instrumented contents of myScript.js
  // ...
</script>
```

Because the `src` attribute is still present on the tag when the browser processes it, the browser will ignore the script body and try to make request to "/null" url.

Merge pull request #351 from google/new_buffer

Updating CFF to little-endian and optimizing the event generators.

Updating CFF to little-endian and optimizing the event generators.
Previously event data was in big-endian format and written by the
wtf.io.Buffer type, back when there was interest in supporting browsers
without typed arrays. This commit changes everything to use mapped typed
arrays that result in less code, less runtime generated code (that's faster
by sometimes *a lot*, especially when writing arrays), and generally clean
things up. Events can consume more memory, as now all arguments must be
4b aligned, however 99% of arguments are strings or ints, so that's ok.

The legacy big-endian format is still supported for reading, but code to
write it has been removed.

This also adds a fix for blobs no longer working reliably when passed
between parent/popup and some error message cleanup.

This renames BrowserProvider to ChromeDebugProvider to more closely match
what it does. It changes the transmission format of the timeline debug
data to a flatter filtered structure that is simpler/smaller to serialize.
Instead of sending the timeline data as it arrives it batches it up and
sends it every second. This has the possibility of losing up to a second
of data, but in the future can be made more robust.

This also adds the chrome:tracing functionality into the
ChromeDebugProvider with some efficiency fixes, such as filtering of the
data and transformation into a flatter structer in the extension before
transmitting it to the provider to get around the nasty O(n^2) string
transfer issues in in the ChromePort implementation. Needs an icon and
some UI cleanup, but it's usable now.

Improving performance of snapshotting in Chrome.
This uses blob URLs to shift data from the page to the UI, dramatically
increasing performance and solving crashes with large traces.

This also fixes a small message issue in the DomChannel that was causing
spurious messages on the page.

Changing flow API.
Flows now have different semantics that match real usage a bit better.
branchFlow takes a flow name and (in a bit) a value, extendFlow takes a
stage name and a value, and terminateFlow takes only a value. The analysis
side needs a lot of cleanup, but the tracing now works.
Flow logic is also now encapsulated in the flow APIs, removing the opt_flow
param from scope enter.

A bunch of breaking changes that get the file format/trace API in a good place.

Adding a static wtf.trace.scopeLeave to make it easier to write custom
scope management code.
This means that instead of if (!scope) { scope.leave(); } one can just
use wtf.trace.leaveScope(scope). This also helps the compiler by having
goog.nullFunction and goog.identityFunction used instead of custom mock
objects.

This speeds up the benchmark form 0.00088ms/scope to 0.00033ms/scope.

Updating the shim to the latest API version.
This also adds a version check to make the shim only work with compatible
API versions.

Adding trace file parse error reporting and a dialog.
It's pretty simple, but better than nothing.

Switching event argument order (fixes #127).
This moves the time argument to the end, with the flow argument preceeding
it if it is present (such as in scopes). This makes it possible to call
generated event functions with the same signature they are created with,
which is the 99% case (only GC events use the time override right now):
'foo(uint32 a)' -> fooEvent(123)

Fixing up binary/json file headers to include general flags and metadata.
This allows for additional flags to be added in the future, custom metadata
(things like extensions loaded when tracing, etc), and cleaner version
number sharing between the trace and analysis pieces of code.

Making event names consistent.
Also adding a wtf.trace.timeStamp method.
This breaks the wire format of both binary and JSON traces.

Adding the skeleton work for the wtf-json file format.
This lets you open both wtf-trace and wtf-json files in the UI. If the
files are loaded together (dragged in/ctrl-o/etc) then they will be
loaded into the same database correctly. The loader isn't currently
implemented, pending some TraceSource cleanup.

Splitting event dispatch from the TraceListener.
This makes loading/etc slightly faster for DB-based apps as no events
need to be setup/emitted. This will also help make the eventual
unclosurizing of scripts a little cleaner.

Changing the generated event functions to be more efficient.
They now use captured closure variables instead of 'this' to get access
to global data structures (such as the current session). Since event
lifetime is a bit odd (independent of session lifetime, most created before
the TraceManager is around, and required at invocation time) there
are some hoops to jump through here, such as the 'session pointer' hack
to give the generated functions access to the current session pointer.

The overhead of each trace function call goes down by about 0.03ms with
this - about 4% (I think).
